                <note type="summary">
                    
                        
                            <p>This letter was written by Monsignor Michael O&#39;Riordan (1857-1919), rector at the Irish College in Rome, to Bishop Edward Thomas O&#39;Dwyer (1842-1917), who served as the Bishop of Limerick from 1888 until his death.      This letter concerns O’Riordan’s reaction to the Easter Rising. O’Riordan is critical of the excessive British response to the Rising. Had the executive shown greater leniency the insurgents, who were to become immortal heroes, would probably have been instead regarded as thoughtless youths. He also refers to the death of Francis Sheehy Skeffington (1878 – 1916), an Irish, pacifist, writer and feminist who had adopted his wife Hanna Sheehy&#39;s surname. Skeffington was executed on the morning of 26 April 1916, along with two other civilians who were shot by firing squad on the orders of Captain John Bowen-Colthurst, an experienced officer of the Royal Irish Rifles. Colthurst would later be court-martialed by the British authorities for his actions. O&#39; Riordan states that the execution was </p>
                        
                    
